#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"observers\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1321
#, no-wrap
msgid "Observers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1324
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"defining-observers\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1324
#, no-wrap
msgid "Defining Observers"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1327
msgid ""
"If you are listening for many events on a given model, you may use observers "
"to group all of your listeners into a single class. Observer classes have "
"method names which reflect the Eloquent events you wish to listen for. Each "
"of these methods receives the affected model as their only argument. The "
"`make:observer` Artisan command is the easiest way to create a new observer "
"class:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1329
#, no-wrap
msgid "    php artisan make:observer UserObserver --model=User\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1331
msgid ""
"This command will place the new observer in your `App/Observers` "
"directory. If this directory does not exist, Artisan will create it for "
"you. Your fresh observer will look like the following:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1335 docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1410
#, no-wrap
msgid "    namespace App\\Observers;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1350
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    class UserObserver\n"
"    {\n"
"        /**\n"
"         * Handle the User \"created\" event.\n"
"         *\n"
"         * @param  \\App\\Models\\User  $user\n"
"         * @return void\n"
"         */\n"
"        public function created(User $user)\n"
"        {\n"
"            //\n"
"        }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1361
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        /**\n"
"         * Handle the User \"updated\" event.\n"
"         *\n"
"         * @param  \\App\\Models\\User  $user\n"
"         * @return void\n"
"         */\n"
"        public function updated(User $user)\n"
"        {\n"
"            //\n"
"        }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1372
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        /**\n"
"         * Handle the User \"deleted\" event.\n"
"         *\n"
"         * @param  \\App\\Models\\User  $user\n"
"         * @return void\n"
"         */\n"
"        public function deleted(User $user)\n"
"        {\n"
"            //\n"
"        }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1384
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        /**\n"
"         * Handle the User \"forceDeleted\" event.\n"
"         *\n"
"         * @param  \\App\\Models\\User  $user\n"
"         * @return void\n"
"         */\n"
"        public function forceDeleted(User $user)\n"
"        {\n"
"            //\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1386
msgid ""
"To register an observer, you need to call the `observe` method on the model "
"you wish to observe. You may register observers in the `boot` method of your "
"application's `App\\Providers\\EventServiceProvider` service provider:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1389
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    use App\\Models\\User;\n"
"    use App\\Observers\\UserObserver;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1399
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    /**\n"
"     * Register any events for your application.\n"
"     *\n"
"     * @return void\n"
"     */\n"
"    public function boot()\n"
"    {\n"
"        User::observe(UserObserver::class);\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1401
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"> {tip} There are additional events an observer can listen to, such as "
"`saving` and `retrieved`. These events are described within the "
"[events](#events) documentation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1403
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"observers-and-database-transactions\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1403
#, no-wrap
msgid "Observers & Database Transactions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1406
msgid ""
"When models are being created within a database transaction, you may want to "
"instruct an observer to only execute its event handlers after the database "
"transaction is committed. You may accomplish this by defining an "
"`$afterCommit` property on the observer. If a database transaction is not in "
"progress, the event handlers will execute immediately:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1421
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    class UserObserver\n"
"    {\n"
"        /**\n"
"         * Handle events after all transactions are committed.\n"
"         *\n"
"         * @var bool\n"
"         */\n"
"        public $afterCommit = true;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1433
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        /**\n"
"         * Handle the User \"created\" event.\n"
"         *\n"
"         * @param  \\App\\Models\\User  $user\n"
"         * @return void\n"
"         */\n"
"        public function created(User $user)\n"
"        {\n"
"            //\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1435
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"muting-events\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1435
#, no-wrap
msgid "Muting Events"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1438
msgid ""
"You may occasionally need to temporarily \"mute\" all events fired by a "
"model. You may achieve this using the `withoutEvents` method. The "
"`withoutEvents` method accepts a closure as its only argument. Any code "
"executed within this closure will not dispatch model events, and any value "
"returned by the closure will be returned by the `withoutEvents` method:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1443
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    $user = User::withoutEvents(function () use () {\n"
"        User::findOrFail(1)->delete();\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1446
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"        return User::find(2);\n"
"    });\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1448
#, no-wrap
msgid "<a name=\"saving-a-single-model-without-events\"></a>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1448
#, no-wrap
msgid "Saving A Single Model Without Events"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1451
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may wish to \"save\" a given model without dispatching any "
"events. You may accomplish this using the `saveQuietly` method:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1453
#, no-wrap
msgid "    $user = User::findOrFail(1);\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1455
#, no-wrap
msgid "    $user->name = 'Victoria Faith';\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/8.x/eloquent.md:1456
#, no-wrap
msgid "    $user->saveQuietly();\n"
msgstr ""
